TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chatterjee, Satyajit
AU  - Eyigungor, Burcu
T1  - Policy Inertia, Election Uncertainty, and Incumbency Disadvantage of Political Parties
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdaa010
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 87
IS  - 6
SP  - 2600
EP  - 2638
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We document that postwar U.S. elections show a strong pattern of “incumbency disadvantage”: if a party has held the presidency of the country or the governorship of a state for some time, that party tends to lose popularity in the subsequent election. We show that this fact can be explained by a combination of policy inertia and unpredictability in election outcomes. A quantitative analysis shows that the observed magnitude of incumbency disadvantage can arise in several different models of policy inertia. Normative and positive implications of policy inertia leading to incumbency disadvantage are explored.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdaa010
ER  - 



